    <item>
      <title>Operaismo</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/critical-theory/domains/marxism/domains/autonomism/domains/operaismo/terms/operaismo/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 03 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/critical-theory/domains/marxism/domains/autonomism/domains/operaismo/terms/operaismo/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Operaismo (Italian: workerism) is the political and intellectual tendency that emerged in Italy in the early 1960s, associated with the journals &lt;em&gt;Quaderni Rossi&lt;/em&gt; (1961–1965) and &lt;em&gt;Classe Operaia&lt;/em&gt; (1964–1967) and with figures including Raniero Panzieri, &lt;a href=&#34;../../general/domains/people/mario-tronti.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Mario Tronti&lt;/a&gt;, and Antonio Negri. Operaismo&amp;rsquo;s foundational move is a Copernican inversion of the relationship between capital and &lt;a href=&#34;./labor.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;labor&lt;/a&gt;: rather than studying capital&amp;rsquo;s laws of motion and deriving the working class as a consequence, operaismo starts from working-&lt;a href=&#34;./class-struggle.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;class struggle&lt;/a&gt; and derives capital&amp;rsquo;s development as a response.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
